  "articleSummary": "The article argues that semantic vector search is not a universal solution but a specialized tool best used in hybrid architectures alongside lexical and fuzzy search methods. It emphasizes understanding the distinct engineering challenges of search tasks—ranging from exact matches (e.g., database queries) to intent-based relevance (e.g., article recommendations)—and highlights when vector search excels (e.g., RAG, multilingual queries, intent-driven retrieval) versus when lexical tools like `tsvector` or `pg_trgm` are more appropriate. Key technologies discussed include embedding models, HNSW indexing, and hybrid ranking via RRF, with a focus on practical use cases like semantic deduplication and intent-based filtering. The tone is analytical and educational, targeting engineers designing search systems, using metaphors like \"win friends and lovers\" to underscore the persuasive power of nuanced technical decisions.",
